        content: `Sportsbooks calculate parlay payouts by multiplying the decimal odds of each leg together.\n\n**Example:**\n- Leg 1: -110 = 1.909 decimal\n- Leg 2: -110 = 1.909 decimal\n- Leg 3: +150 = 2.500 decimal\n\nCombined odds: 1.909 × 1.909 × 2.500 = 9.11\n\nA $100 bet returns $911 total ($811 profit).\n\n**Why the house edge compounds:** Each -110 leg carries about a 4.5% house edge. On a single bet, that's manageable. But on a three-leg parlay, the effective house edge jumps to roughly 13%. On a five-leg parlay, it's over 20%.\n\nThis is why professional bettors rarely play parlays. The short-term excitement of big payouts masks the long-term mathematical disadvantage.\n\n**Correlated parlays:** The one exception where parlays can have value. If your legs are related — like betting a game's Under AND the underdog (low-scoring games favor underdogs) — the true probability of both hitting is higher than the odds imply. Most books try to block correlated parlays, but some slip through.`
